":"okolo 1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1540":"1540","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","England":"Anglie"},"da":{"about 1480–Deceased":"omkring 1480–Afdød","1480–1540":"1480–1540","1500–Female":"1500–Afdød","1480–Female":"1480–Afdød","about 1480":"omkring 1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1540":"1540","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","England":"England"},"nl":{"about 1480–Deceased":"circa 1480–Overleden","1480–1540":"1480–1540","1500–Female":"1500–Overleden","1480–Female":"1480–Overleden","about 1480":"circa 1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1540":"1540","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1480–Deceased":"about 1480–Deceased","1480–1540":"1480–1540","1500–Female":"1500–Deceased","1480–Female":"1480–Deceased","about 1480":"about 1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1540":"1540","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Shaw","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): from Middle English <i>s(c)hawe</i>, <i>s(c)haghe</i> ‘small wood, grove, thicket’ (Old English <i>sceaga</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a small wood, or habitational, for someone from any of the many places so named. <i>Shaw</i> and <i>Shawe</i> are most frequent in Lancashire and Yorkshire, where Shaw in Oldham (Lancashire) may be a principal source of the surname. The English and Lowland Scottish surname was also established in Ireland in the 17th century.","Scottish: shortened form of various surnames from the Gaelic personal name <i>Sitheach</i>, derived from <i>sithech</i> ‘wolf’.","Irish (Down and Antrim): adopted for <b>Ó Síthigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Sítheach</i>’, a personal name based on <i>sítheach</i> ‘peaceful’. Compare   Sheehy  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Show","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cumberland): probably a variant of   Shaw  , perhaps representing a blend in Middle English of Old English <i>sceaga</i> and Old Norse <i>skógr</i>, both meaning ‘wood’.","Perhaps an Americanized form of German   Schau  ."]},{"name":"Sheehy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, Aisling, Brigid, Declan, Egan, Eoin, Finbar, Ronan.","Irish (Limerick and Kerry): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Síthigh</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Sítheach</i>’, or <b>Mac Síthigh</b> ‘son of <i>Sítheach</i>’, a form of the Irish personal name <i>Síodhach</i> ‘peaceful’, from the adjective <i>sítheach</i> ‘peaceful’ or ‘other worldly’ (see   Sheehan  ). The noun <i>síth</i>, from which this adjective derives, means basically ‘settlement’, hence both ‘peace’ and ‘place inhabited by other world beings’. This name was established in Ireland from the early 14th century, when a branch of the Scottish McDonnells, descended from <i>Sítheach</i>, great-grandson of Domhnaill, settled in the country."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: Bitter; Marion is the French form."],"variants":[{"name":"Marion","meanings":["Originally a medieval French diminutive form of   Marie  , introduced to Britain in the Middle Ages. In some places it was taken as a pet form of   Margaret   or   Margery .  As a male name, it is an altered form of the Continental male name <i>Marian</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>Marianus</i> (from   Marius  ), but is now rarely, if ever, used. It was the birth name of the American film star  John Wayne  (  1907–79 )."]},{"name":"Marcia","meanings":["Often used as a feminine equivalent of   Mark  , but in fact a feminine form of <i>Marcius</i>, itself a derivative of   Marcus .  One  St Marcia  is commemorated in a group with Felix, Luciolus, Fortunatus, and others; another with Zenais, Cyria, and Valeria; and a third with Ariston, Crescentian, Eutychian, Urban, Vitalis, Justus, Felicissimus, Felix, and Symphorosa. None is individually very famous."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":69,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":78,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":89,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mary Shaw was born about 1480, in England. She married George McMinn in 1500, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1480–Deceased":"umbes 1480–Surnud","1480–1540":"1480–1540","1500–Female":"1500–Surnud","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","about 1480":"umbes 1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1540":"1540","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1480–Deceased":"noin 1480–Kuollut","1480–1540":"1480–1540","1500–Female":"1500–Kuollut","1480–Female":"1480–Kuollut","about 1480":"noin 1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1540":"1540","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","England":"England"},"fr":{"about 1480–Deceased":"environ 1480–Décédée","1480–1540":"1480–1540","1500–Female":"1500–Décédée","1480–Female":"1480–Décédée","about 1480":"environ 1480","1569":"